### Post 1 — [2026, june 13]
**URL:** https://www.linkedin.com/posts/nickfromseattle_companies-will-burn-six-months-of-ad-spend-activity-7471215215620231168-sLXf

Companies will burn six months of ad spend testing audiences and call it learning.

Ask them to test SEO for six months, and suddenly it's a gamble.

I’ve seen this skepticism a lot. So now we just walk through the maths on the keywords they're already bidding on.

In the US, those clicks cost about $7 each. Rented, every month, forever.

Six months of organic work might mean publishing 60 pages against those same keywords. On past campaigns, that's resulted in as low as $0.50 a click, amortized over the year. And the clicks keep coming after our engagement ends.

It's the same results page, too. The person clicking the organic listing typed the exact query you were paying $7 to appear for.

Of course, clicks still aren't revenue though. Nobody takes a cost-per-click number into a QBR.

So we hold it to the paid standard on purpose. We report ROAS, not ROI, and benchmark first funnel conversion against whatever their best channel does. Most healthy channels sit between 8% and 12%. By month six or seven, the leading indicators point at the same numbers.

Paid earned the right to experiment, while organic never did.

One of these experiments keeps producing after you stop paying for it.

Somehow, that's the one that gets called a gamble.


