### Post 3 — [2026, JUNE]
**URL:** https://www.linkedin.com/posts/nickfromseattle_i-cant-force-you-to-invest-in-quality-content-activity-7332776068396855298-jNQG


Every marketer in fintech, healthcare or compliance I talk to is scared of scaling content output and getting sued for something inside it.

Scaling is only half the problem.

Here's what we've learnt producing content in regulated industries:


1/ Volume isn't the threat. Producing at volume without fact-checking every piece against current regulations is.

Here's what content production actually looks like at CD:
↳ Strategists do the upfront research: customer journey, regulatory framework, content prioritization
↳ Writers draft from your brand guidelines, editorial standards and source material
↳ An agentic workflow fact-checks every draft against current regulations and your technical guidelines
↳ Editors finalize the piece and fact-check it themselves
↳ Subject matter experts review the technical accuracy

The AI-only version of this is what your legal team is scared of. We don't do the AI-only version.


2/ Most "AI fact-checking" is just plugging a draft into Claude.

Fact-checking content at volume is slow, expensive and unglamorous work. Most marketing teams looking at AI to fix it reach for the obvious move: paste the draft into Claude or ChatGPT and ask it to flag anything wrong.

Generic models have no idea what your brand guidelines say, no idea which regulatory framework you operate inside, no live access to current sources.

What we run is a custom agentic workflow connected to an MCP server with your brand, editorial, technical and style guidelines loaded. Multiple models handle different sub-tasks: live web research, source parsing, claim synthesis. All grounded in your context.


3/ Most of what our QA agent catches is sourcing problems your reviewers wouldn't catch on the second pass.

Last healthcare run flagged 5 articles. None of them were technically incorrect. They'd leaned on one set of scientific sources without acknowledging the supplementary research that contradicted them. The kind of thing the scientific community would have torched.

The agent doesn't replace the writer, editor or subject matter expert. It catches what they'd miss reviewing a stack of pieces back to back.


If you're scaling content production in fintech, healthcare or compliance and want to see what our agent flags on your work, send me a URL.

